{"cursor":"11118","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn linear algebra, the 'dual numbers' extend the real numbers by adjoining one\nnew element Îµ with the property Îµ 2 = 0 (Îµ is nilpotent). The\ncollection of dual numbers forms a particular two-dimensional commutative unital\nassociative algebra over the real numbers. Every dual number has the form z = a\n+ bÎµ with a and b uniquely determined real numbers. The plane of all dual\nnumbers is an \"alternative complex plane\" that complements the ordinary complex\nnumber plane 'C' and the 'motor plane D' of split-complex numbers.\n","linknr":284,"url":"Dual_number","recorded":1371241592,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Dual_number&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Dual_number&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Dual_(grammatical_number)","/wiki/Linear_algebra","/wiki/Real_number","/wiki/Nilpotent","/wiki/Hamel_dimension","/wiki/Commutative","/wiki/Unital_algebra","/wiki/Associative_algebra","/wiki/Complex_number","/wiki/Split-complex_number","#Linear_representation","#Geometry","#Cycles","#Algebraic_properties","#Generalization","#Differentiation","#Superspace","#Division","#Exponentiation","#See_also","#References","/w/index.php?title=Dual